                     <title key="work_3885">De XII abusiuis saeculi</title>
                     <rubric>Incipit liber sancti Cypriani. martiris de duodecim abusiuis seculi</rubric>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem class="#theologica" n="3" xml:id="MS_Bodl_1-item3">
                     <locus from="25v">(fol. 25v)</locus>
                     <title key="work_15308" type="desc">Theological treatises</title>
                     <title key="work_14583" type="desc">Sermons</title>
                     <note>Seventy-five short treatises, chiefly sermons, among which the only one which bears an author's name is (fol. 31v) 'Tractatus sancti Augustini de mammona iniquitatis', sermon no. 113 in Migne's Patrologia</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem class="#sermones" n="4" xml:id="MS_Bodl_1-item4">
                     <locus from="74v">(fol. 74v)</locus>
                     <author key="person_9865788"><supplied>Hugh of Saint-Victor</supplied></author>
                     <title key="work_5917"><supplied>Miscellanea</supplied></title>
                     <bibl>I. 73</bibl>
                     <rubric>Incipit tractatus de tribus naturis et vndecim speciebus ignis</rubric>
                     <incipit>Tres sunt nature ignis</incipit>
                     <note>At fol. 75v is 'allegorica expositio precedentium specierum'</note>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem n="5" xml:id="MS_Bodl_1-item5">
                     <locus from="79">(fol. 79)</locus>
                     <author key="person_66806872">Augustine</author>
                     <title key="work_779">De sancta uirginitate</title>
                     <note>(abbreviated)</note>
                     <rubric>Tractatus sancti Augustini de sancta uirginitate</rubric>
                     <incipit>Jure diuino continentia</incipit>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem>
                     <note>On fol. 84v are some moral and witty sayings, chiefly in verse (13th cent.), such as 'Denigrat meritum dantis mora ...', 'Sidonius [?]. Non est maior gloria dixisse quod noueris quam siluisse quod nescias'.</note>
